{"status": "active", "_id": "505a1572fd48f82823f4625a", "name": "Core Analyzer", "preferred_support_tool": "_url", "preferred_support_url": "http://core-analyzer.sourceforge.net", "icon_url": "http://sourceforge.net/p/core-analyzer/icon", "labels": [], "private": false, "creation_date": "2011-06-17", "url": "http://sourceforge.net/p/core-analyzer/", "short_description": "Core analyzer is a power tool to debug memory issues. With ever increasing complexity and dataset size of application programs, it is very challenging to find the root cause of a memory bug. Programmers often use debugger to go through many contexts or data objects in order to find a variable, an object or a reference of interest. However, the task is boring, prone to error and usually fruitless. By parsing a core dump file or reading a live process's memory, core analyzer is able to scan the target's heap data for memory corruption, search the whole address space for data object's references, or analyze memory pattern for a given range. It is thorough, labor-free, and insightful. I use the tool on daily basis and it is proved to be invaluable to debug many tough issues.\r\n\r\nThe tool supports x86_64 architecture including Windows/RedHat/SUSE/MacOSX (both 32-bit and 64-bit).\r\n\r\nFor more information, please see the project's web site.", "summary": "A power tool to debug core dump, memory corruption, optimized code.", "tools": [{"sourceforge_group_id": 557860, "mount_point": "summary", "name": "summary", "label": "Summary"}, {"mount_point": "downloads", "name": "files", "label": "Files"}, {"mount_point": "code", "name": "svn", "label": "Code"}, {"mount_point": "news", "name": "blog", "label": "News"}, {"mount_point": "reviews", "name": "reviews", "label": "Reviews"}, {"mount_point": "support", "name": "support", "label": "Support"}, {"mount_point": "tickets", "name": "tickets", "label": "Bug Report"}, {"mount_point": "activity", "name": "activity", "label": "Activity"}], "video_url": "", "social